  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "If your direct customer cohort is not on Facebook (specially in B2B), how do you steer that social channel to pull in audiences for your business?",
  "response": "If your direct customer cohort is not on Facebook, especially in a B2B context, it\u2019s essential to adjust your strategy to make the most out of your social media efforts and steer the platform to benefit your business. Here are several strategies:\n\n### 1. **Content Tailoring and Diversification**\n   - **Share Industry News**: Post content relevant to the industry you\u2019re serving. This may include news, trends, or advancements that can attract a professional audience.\n   - **Educational Content**: Create and share content that educates and informs\u2014think webinars, whitepapers, case studies, and how-to guides that professionals in your target industry would find valuable.\n   - **Expert Opinions and Interviews**: Feature interviews with industry experts or thought leaders, providing insights that can appeal to your B2B audience.\n\n### 2. **Targeted Advertising**\n   - **Facebook Ads**: Use Facebook\u2019s robust advertising features to target specific professions, industries, or companies. Detailed targeting options allow you to reach decision-makers and influencers within your desired market.\n   - **Custom Audiences**: Upload lists of emails from existing contacts, subscribers, or customers to create custom audiences that ensure your ads reach the right people.\n\n### 3. **Leveraging Groups and Communities**\n   - **Professional and Industry Groups**: Participate in or create Facebook groups centered around your industry. Engage actively by sharing valuable content and initiating discussions.\n   - **Peer Networking**: Encourage employees or brand advocates to join relevant groups, participate in the conversation, and share insights.\n\n### 4. **Content Amplification**\n   - **Share Across Platforms**: Ensure that the content posted on Facebook is also shared on other social channels where your audience is more active, such as LinkedIn, Twitter, or industry-specific forums.\n   - **Influencer Partnerships**: Collaborate with industry influencers who can share your content on Facebook, helping to increase your reach within professional circles.\n\n### 5. **Engagement and Interaction**\n   - **Answer Questions**: Proactively engage with users who comment on your posts or ask questions. This builds trust and positions your business as knowledgeable and responsive.\n   - **Live Q&A Sessions**: Host live Q&A sessions on Facebook to discuss industry-related topics or solutions your business offers.\n\n### 6. **Integrate with Other Marketing Efforts**\n   - **Event Promotion**: Use Facebook to promote webinars, conferences, or other virtual events, driving registration through valuable content.\n   - **Cross-Promotion**: Integrate Facebook activities with email marketing campaigns, blog content, and SEO strategies for a more coherent approach.\n\n### 7. **Track and Optimize**\n   - **Analytics**: Utilize Facebook Insights and third-party tools to analyze engagement metrics. Adjust content strategy based on performance, focusing more on the types of posts that resonate with your audience.\n   - **Testing**: Continually test new content types and posting strategies to see what works best for attracting and engaging your target B2B audience.\n\nBy implementing these strategies, you can leverage Facebook as a tool to increase visibility and engagement from your professional audience, even if they are not typically active on the platform.",
